export const story = {"seriesId":"mrs-webster-takes-everything-literally","storyId":"mrs-webster-takes-everything-literally","storyKey":"mrs-webster-takes-everything-literally/mrs-webster-takes-everything-literally","seriesTitle":"Mrs. Webster Takes Everything Literally","seriesDescription":"When Marcus arrives at Brookdale Elementary, everyone warns him about Mrs. Webster, the teacher who takes everything literally. But after weeks of disasters, he starts to suspect the truth: Mrs. Webster isn't confused at all. She's having the time of her life.","title":"Mrs. Webster Takes Everything Literally","author":"The New Kid","description":"When Marcus arrives at Brookdale Elementary, everyone warns him about Mrs. Webster, the teacher who takes everything literally. But after weeks of disasters, he starts to suspect the truth: Mrs. Webster isn't confused at all. She's having the time of her life.","ageRange":"7-10","genre":"Humor","tags":["school","teachers","wordplay","language","humor","mystery"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"The Warnings","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# The Warnings\n\nOn my first day at Brookdale Elementary, three different kids warned me about Mrs. Webster. I should have listened.\n\nThe first warning came from a girl named Destiny at the lockers. She had braids with little purple beads that clicked when she moved her head, and she looked at me like I was walking into a burning building.\n\n\"You're the new kid, right? Marcus?\"\n\n\"Yeah,\" I said, shoving my backpack into my locker. \"How'd you know?\"\n\n\"Small school.\" She leaned in close. \"Listen. You have Mrs. Webster for fourth period. Whatever you do, *don't use idioms*.\"\n\nI blinked at her. \"Don't use what?\"\n\n\"Idioms. You know, like 'break a leg' or 'piece of cake' or—\" She stopped herself, looking around nervously. \"Just... say exactly what you mean. Nothing else. Trust me.\"\n\nBefore I could ask what she was talking about, she clicked away down the hall.\n\nThe second warning came from a random kid at the water fountain. He was short, had glasses, and spoke in a whisper.\n\n\"Hey. New kid. Mrs. Webster's class?\"\n\n\"Yeah?\"\n\n\"She makes everything weird. Just... be careful.\"\n\nThen he was gone.\n\nThe third warning came from a tall kid named Kevin who cornered me outside the classroom door. He had the look of someone who'd seen things. Terrible things.\n\n\"Dude,\" he said. \"She's actually insane.\"\n\n\"Who, Mrs. Webster?\"\n\n\"Last month, Tyler said he was going to 'hit the books' and she handed him an actual dictionary and told him to swing hard.\" Kevin shook his head slowly. \"He got detention for property damage.\"\n\nI laughed. \"That's a good prank.\"\n\nKevin didn't laugh. \"It wasn't a prank.\"\n\nI figured the kids at Brookdale Elementary were just messing with the new guy. Classic move. Make up some wild story about a teacher, watch the new kid panic. I wasn't going to fall for it.\n\nMrs. Webster seemed completely normal. She had silver-streaked hair in a neat bun, reading glasses on a beaded chain, and a cardigan with patches on the elbows. She smiled warmly when I introduced myself and showed me to my desk. Her voice was kind. Her handwriting on the board was perfect.\n\n*These kids are ridiculous*, I thought. *She's the most normal teacher I've ever had*.\n\nThe class went fine. We read a poem about the ocean. We discussed metaphors (which are apparently different from idioms, but I still wasn't totally clear on either). Mrs. Webster asked good questions and actually listened to the answers.\n\nSee? Normal.\n\nThen, at the end of class, my stomach growled. Loudly.\n\nMrs. Webster looked up. \"Hungry, Mr. Chen?\"\n\n\"Starving,\" I said, without thinking. \"I could eat a horse.\"\n\nThe room went silent. Every single kid turned to look at me. Destiny's beads froze mid-click. Kevin slowly put his head down on his desk.\n\nMrs. Webster adjusted her glasses, and I could have sworn I saw the corner of her mouth twitch.\n\n\"A horse,\" she said thoughtfully. \"That's quite an appetite. Would you prefer it grilled or roasted? I should warn you, the cafeteria doesn't typically stock horse, but I could make some calls. There's a farm two towns over. Do you have any allergies? Would you like hay on the side?\"\n\nI stared at her.\n\nShe stared back, perfectly pleasant, pen poised over her notebook as if she was genuinely ready to write down my order.\n\n\"I... I didn't mean...\"\n\n\"Of course, we'd need parental permission for that kind of meal,\" she continued. \"It's quite a large portion. Should I send a note home?\"\n\n\"No! I just—I meant I'm really hungry. Regular hungry. For regular food.\"\n\n\"Ah.\" She smiled and set down her pen. \"Then might I suggest the cafeteria's Tuesday special? I hear the meatloaf is acceptable.\"\n\nThe bell rang. Kids scrambled for the door. As I walked out, dazed, I glanced back.\n\nMrs. Webster was writing something in a small leather notebook. And I could have sworn—just for a second—she was smiling.\n\nNot a confused smile. Not a *what a strange boy* smile.\n\nA satisfied smile.\n\nLike she'd just won something.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"Learning the Hard Way","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# Learning the Hard Way\n\nBy Friday, I had made four mistakes. Each one worse than the last.\n\n**Monday**: We were discussing the American Revolution, and Mrs. Webster asked if anyone had questions. I raised my hand and said, \"I'm all ears.\"\n\nShe stopped mid-sentence. Adjusted her glasses. Tilted her head.\n\n\"All ears?\" she repeated. \"My goodness, Mr. Chen. That sounds like a serious medical condition. Should I call your parents? The school nurse? Ears are important, but you do need other body parts. A brain, for instance. Lungs. Perhaps a spleen.\"\n\nThe class giggled. I sank into my chair.\n\n\"I just meant I'm listening,\" I mumbled.\n\n\"Ah,\" she said. \"Then perhaps say *that* next time.\"\n\n**Tuesday**: I needed to borrow a pencil. Destiny tried to stop me—actually grabbed my arm—but I'd already said it.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster? Can I lend you my pencil? I mean—can you lend me—wait—\"\n\nToo late.\n\nShe pulled out a small notepad. \"Certainly, Mr. Chen. Standard lending terms apply. The pencil will be due back by end of class. Interest rate is two percent, payable in eraser shavings. Late returns will incur a fee of one mechanical pencil lead per day. Do you accept these terms?\"\n\n\"I just need to write my name on the worksheet.\"\n\n\"The terms, Mr. Chen?\"\n\n\"...I accept.\"\n\nShe handed me the pencil with a completely straight face. But when I looked up, she was writing in that leather notebook again.\n\n**Wednesday**: Destiny coached me at lunch.\n\n\"Okay,\" she said, stabbing her tater tots with a fork. \"Here's the deal. Only say exactly what you mean. No expressions. No figures of speech. If you're tired, don't say 'I'm dead tired.' Don't say 'I could sleep for a year.' Say 'I am experiencing fatigue.'\"\n\n\"That sounds like a robot.\"\n\n\"Better a robot than whatever Kevin is.\" She pointed across the cafeteria, where Kevin was loudly complaining to his friends. \"He says an idiom like once an hour. He never learns. Last week he told her he was 'feeling under the weather' and she offered him an umbrella.\"\n\nI practiced. I was going to be careful.\n\n**Thursday**: It was raining. Hard.\n\nI walked into class, dripping wet, and before I could stop myself, I said, \"Wow, it's really raining cats and dogs out there.\"\n\nMrs. Webster went to the window. She looked outside for a long, long moment. Then she turned back to me with what I can only describe as disappointment.\n\n\"I don't see any cats, Mr. Chen. Or dogs. Just rain.\" She sighed. \"What a shame. I do enjoy animals.\"\n\n\"It's just an expression—\"\n\n\"Perhaps you heard barking? The wind can sound like barking sometimes.\"\n\n\"I didn't—\"\n\n\"I'll keep watching. Just in case.\"\n\nShe stared out the window for the entire reading period. Every few minutes, she'd murmur, \"Still no dogs.\"\n\n**Friday**: The worst one.\n\nI was trying to move desks and I said—without thinking, because apparently I never think—\"Hey, Mrs. Webster? Could you take a seat?\"\n\nShe picked up the chair next to her. Lifted it right off the ground.\n\n\"Certainly. Where would you like me to take it? The principal's office? The cafeteria? The parking lot seems inconvenient, but I'm willing to make the walk.\"\n\n\"I meant—\"\n\n\"The gymnasium? There's a basketball game tonight. They might need extra seating.\"\n\n\"Please put the chair down.\"\n\nShe set it down gently. Smiled. Wrote something in her notebook.\n\nAnd that's when I noticed it.\n\nShe adjusted her glasses *before* I finished speaking. The mouth twitch happened *before* she delivered the response. She always knew what was coming. She was always ready.\n\nToo ready.\n\n\"Hey,\" I said to Destiny after class. \"Does Mrs. Webster seem... fast to you?\"\n\n\"What do you mean?\"\n\n\"Like, she always has the perfect response. Immediately. It's like she knows what we're going to say before we say it.\"\n\nDestiny frowned. \"I mean, she's been teaching for a while...\"\n\n\"No, that's not—\" I struggled to explain. \"Today she picked up the chair before I finished my sentence. She was already reaching for it.\"\n\nDestiny was quiet for a moment.\n\n\"Marcus,\" she said slowly. \"Are you saying you think she's doing it on purpose?\"\n\nI looked back at the classroom. Mrs. Webster was erasing the board, humming quietly to herself.\n\n\"I don't know yet,\" I said. \"But I'm going to find out.\"\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Webster Twinkle","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# The Webster Twinkle\n\nI decided to stop talking and start watching.\n\nFor one whole week, I didn't use a single idiom. I spoke like Destiny—careful, precise, almost robotic. \"May I please use the restroom?\" instead of \"I gotta run.\" \"The assignment is difficult\" instead of \"This is killing me.\"\n\nIt was exhausting. But it let me pay attention to everyone else.\n\nAnd that's when I saw it.\n\nOn Tuesday, Kevin finished his math test early. He leaned back in his chair, stretched, and announced to no one in particular, \"That test was a piece of cake.\"\n\nMrs. Webster didn't even look up from her desk. She just reached into her bottom drawer—the one she never opened—and pulled out a small Tupperware container.\n\nInside was a slice of chocolate cake.\n\n\"Would you like a fork, Kevin?\" she asked, setting it on his desk. \"Since the test was a piece of cake, it only seems fair that you should have one.\"\n\nKevin stared at the cake. Then at her. Then at the cake again.\n\n\"I... what?\"\n\n\"The cake, Kevin. You said the test was cake. Here it is. Enjoy.\"\n\nShe'd had cake in her desk. *Ready*. Like she knew someone would say it.\n\nI wrote in my notebook: *Prepared in advance. Evidence of planning.*\n\nOn Wednesday, a girl named Sophie was nervous about the school play. She was playing a tree, which doesn't seem like a hard role, but Sophie was very serious about it.\n\n\"Wish me luck, Mrs. Webster,\" she said. \"I'm about to go break a leg!\"\n\nMrs. Webster's hand was already moving toward the phone. *Before Sophie finished the sentence.*\n\n\"Break a leg?\" Mrs. Webster lifted the receiver. \"That sounds terribly painful. Should I call an ambulance? The hospital? Your parents will want to know about your plans.\"\n\n\"No! I meant—it's theater—it means good luck!\"\n\n\"Does it? How odd. It sounds like it means 'break a leg.'\" She set down the phone. \"Perhaps the theater should reconsider its vocabulary.\"\n\nI wrote: *Phone in hand before sentence ended. Anticipation.*\n\nOn Thursday, I made my biggest discovery.\n\nWe were talking about the Revolutionary War again, and Mrs. Webster used an idiom. She said the colonists \"let the cat out of the bag\" when they revealed their plans to the British.\n\nA normal idiom. Used correctly.\n\nShe knew what it meant. She *knew*.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster,\" I said, carefully. \"What does 'let the cat out of the bag' mean?\"\n\nShe smiled. \"It means to reveal a secret, Mr. Chen. It comes from an old marketplace trick where sellers would—\" She stopped. Looked at me. Really looked at me, for the first time.\n\nSomething flickered in her eyes. A sparkle. A gleam.\n\nAnd then it was gone, and she continued the lesson.\n\nBut I'd seen it. I'd *seen* it.\n\nAt lunch, I showed Destiny my notes.\n\n\"Look,\" I said. \"She knows every idiom. She uses them correctly when she's teaching. She only pretends not to understand when *we* use them.\"\n\nDestiny read through my observations. Her eyebrows went up.\n\n\"The cake,\" she said. \"She had *cake* in her desk?\"\n\n\"Ready to go. Tupperware and everything.\"\n\n\"That's... actually kind of impressive.\"\n\n\"And there's something else.\" I pointed to my last note. \"When she does it—right before she responds—there's this thing in her eyes. This... sparkle. Like she's about to tell a joke and she's trying not to laugh.\"\n\nDestiny looked at me. \"What are you calling it?\"\n\nI hadn't thought about that. But now, looking at my notes, there was only one thing to call it.\n\n\"The Webster Twinkle,\" I said. \"That's her tell. That's how you know she's about to do it.\"\n\nDestiny was quiet for a long moment. Then she nodded slowly.\n\n\"Okay,\" she said. \"I believe you. So what do we do about it?\"\n\nI thought about it. If she needed idioms to twist, then the way to prove it—and maybe beat her—was to stop giving her ammunition.\n\n\"We stop using idioms entirely,\" I said. \"We speak like robots. Perfectly literal, perfectly precise. If I'm right, she won't be able to do anything.\"\n\n\"And if you're wrong?\"\n\nI closed my notebook. \"Then at least I'll stop embarrassing myself five times a week.\"\n\nDestiny grinned. \"Operation: Outsmart the Teacher?\"\n\n\"Operation: Outsmart the Teacher.\"\n\nThe operation, as it turned out, was harder than I expected.\n\nAnd Mrs. Webster was ready for it.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Operation: Outsmart the Teacher","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Operation: Outsmart the Teacher\n\nThe plan was simple: speak like a robot, avoid all idioms, and prove that Mrs. Webster couldn't twist *perfectly literal* statements.\n\nDay One was a success.\n\n\"May I please use the restroom?\" I asked.\n\n\"Of course, Mr. Chen,\" she said. No twinkle. No twist. Just a normal answer.\n\n*Ha*, I thought. *I'm winning*.\n\n\"May I please sharpen my pencil at the designated pencil-sharpening station?\"\n\n\"Certainly.\"\n\nDestiny gave me a thumbs-up from across the room. Kevin looked confused, but Kevin always looked confused.\n\nDay Two was also a success. I spoke in complete, literal sentences. I said \"I don't understand this math problem\" instead of \"this is making my head spin.\" I said \"I'd like to ask a question\" instead of \"can I pick your brain?\"\n\nMrs. Webster watched me with what I can only describe as *interest*. But she didn't do anything.\n\nBy Day Three, I was feeling confident. Maybe too confident.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster?\" I said. \"I need to get my notebook from my bag.\"\n\nShe tilted her head. Adjusted her glasses.\n\n*Uh oh.*\n\n\"Which bag, Mr. Chen?\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\n\"Which bag? Paper bag? Plastic bag? Sleeping bag? Punching bag?\" She pulled out a notepad. \"I'll need you to be more specific. The school has a diverse collection of bags. I wouldn't want to bring you the wrong one.\"\n\n\"My... my backpack. The bag on my back. That I brought to school. With my stuff in it.\"\n\n\"Ah. The personal carrying device you transport on your shoulders. Why didn't you say so?\"\n\nShe smiled. There was the twinkle.\n\n*She's changing the rules*, I realized. *She knows I know*.\n\nAt lunch, I told Destiny what happened.\n\n\"She took a LITERAL statement literally,\" I said. \"That's not even fair. 'Bag' is a word. It means bag!\"\n\n\"Maybe she's testing you,\" Destiny said. \"To see how far you'll go.\"\n\n\"Or maybe she knows I'm onto her.\"\n\n\"Marcus.\" Destiny leaned forward. \"Have you considered just... asking her?\"\n\n\"Asking her what? 'Hey, are you pretending to misunderstand us on purpose?' She'll just take THAT literally too.\"\n\n\"Then you word it carefully. Really carefully.\"\n\nI thought about it. She was right. The only way to get a real answer was to ask a question she couldn't twist.\n\nBut first, I needed more evidence.\n\nThat afternoon, I tried again.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster? I want to answer the question.\"\n\n\"Which question, Mr. Chen? There are many questions in the universe. 'What is the meaning of life?' 'Why is the sky blue?' 'Where do socks go when they disappear from the dryer?' You'll need to be specific.\"\n\n\"The question. The one you just asked. The one about the Declaration of Independence.\"\n\n\"Ah. That question.\" She nodded. \"Please proceed.\"\n\nI answered the question. She marked it correct. And then she did something she'd never done before.\n\nShe looked right at me. Held my gaze. And her left eye—I swear on my entire pencil collection—*almost winked*.\n\nNot a full wink. Just a tiny flicker. A muscle movement. The ghost of a wink.\n\nBut I saw it.\n\nAfter class, she called me up to her desk.\n\n\"Mr. Chen,\" she said. \"You've been speaking very... precisely lately.\"\n\n\"Thank you?\"\n\n\"It wasn't entirely a compliment.\" She folded her hands. \"Precision is important, but so is creativity. Language is meant to be played with.\"\n\n\"Played with?\"\n\nThe twinkle was back. Full force.\n\n\"Just an observation,\" she said. \"You may go.\"\n\nI walked to the door. Then I stopped.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster?\"\n\n\"Yes, Mr. Chen?\"\n\n\"Tomorrow,\" I said. \"After class. I have a question for you. A very carefully worded question.\"\n\nShe smiled. The real smile, not the customer-service one.\n\n\"I look forward to it,\" she said.\n\nAnd I knew—right then—that she knew exactly what I was going to ask.\n\nAnd she was going to answer honestly.\n\nBecause for some reason, after eight years of waiting, Mrs. Webster had finally found someone who figured out the game.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"The Confession","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# The Confession\n\nI stayed after class.\n\nDestiny had offered to wait outside, but I told her this was something I needed to do alone. She nodded and said, \"Good luck. And I mean that the regular way, not the breaking-legs way.\"\n\nMrs. Webster was erasing the board when the last student left. She didn't turn around, but I could tell she knew I was there.\n\n\"Mr. Chen,\" she said. \"Your carefully worded question?\"\n\nI'd practiced this. All night. Every word.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster,\" I said. \"I have observed that when students use figurative language, you respond with literal interpretations. I have also observed that you use figurative language correctly when teaching. My question is this: Is this behavior intentional?\"\n\nShe stopped erasing. Set down the eraser. Turned around slowly.\n\nFor a moment, she just looked at me. No twinkle. No smile. Just... consideration.\n\nThen she took off her glasses.\n\n\"Mr. Chen,\" she said. \"You're the first student in eight years to figure it out.\"\n\nI let out a breath I didn't know I'd been holding.\n\n\"So it IS on purpose.\"\n\n\"Oh, absolutely.\" She sat down at her desk and gestured for me to pull up a chair. A real chair. Not take it somewhere.\n\n\"Why?\" I asked.\n\nShe laughed. It was a nice laugh, warmer than I expected.\n\n\"Because it's *fun*, Marcus. Because after fifteen years of teaching, I needed something to keep me entertained.\" She leaned back. \"And because—and this is the part nobody believes—it actually works.\"\n\n\"Works how?\"\n\nShe reached into her desk and pulled out a leather notebook. Not the small one she wrote in during class—a bigger one, worn at the edges, stuffed with papers and photos and sticky notes.\n\n\"Fifteen years of this,\" she said, opening it. \"Fifteen years of 'piece of cake' and 'break a leg' and 'hold your horses.'\"\n\nI looked at the pages. There were notes in neat handwriting. *Tyler, September 2019: \"hit the books\" - handed him a dictionary.* *Aisha, March 2022: \"raining cats and dogs\" - spent ten minutes at the window.* *Kevin, basically every week: everything.*\n\n\"You keep track of all of it?\"\n\n\"I keep track of the good ones.\" She turned to a page near the back. \"Here's the thing, Marcus. I used to teach college. English literature. Very serious, very proper. And do you know what I discovered? Nobody laughed. Nobody remembered anything. I'd teach metaphors and similes and the next week, blank stares.\"\n\nShe closed the notebook.\n\n\"Then I came here. Fourth grade. And on my very first day, a student told me she was 'all ears.' And I thought—just for fun—what if I took that literally? So I did. And the whole class laughed. And the next week, when we talked about idioms, every single student remembered what 'all ears' meant. Because they remembered me being ridiculous.\"\n\n\"So it's educational?\"\n\n\"It's hilarious AND educational,\" she said. \"But mostly hilarious. I won't lie to you, Marcus. I do it because it makes me happy. Watching you all try to outsmart me? That's the best part of my day.\"\n\nI thought about all the times she'd gotten me. The horse. The pencil lending terms. The bags.\n\n\"So you're never going to stop.\"\n\n\"Why would I stop? I'm having the time of my life.\" She paused. \"Also, I'm genuinely curious—would you prefer your horse grilled or roasted? You never answered.\"\n\nI laughed. I couldn't help it.\n\n\"Mrs. Webster,\" I said. \"You're kind of a genius.\"\n\n\"Please.\" She waved her hand. \"I'm just a teacher who pays attention to words. Which, by the way, you've started doing too. Have you noticed that? You speak more carefully now. You think before you talk.\"\n\nI hadn't noticed. But she was right.\n\n\"Is that... was that part of the plan?\"\n\nShe smiled the real smile again. \"Words matter, Marcus. Every single one. If I have to make a fool of myself to teach you that, well...\" She shrugged. \"I'm happy to take one for the team.\"\n\nI stood up to leave. Then stopped.\n\n\"Are you going to tell everyone? That I figured it out?\"\n\n\"That's up to you,\" she said. \"You can tell whoever you want. But I should warn you—knowing the secret doesn't make you immune. I'll still get you. I'm very, very good at this.\"\n\nI thought about it. About Destiny, who spoke like a robot. About Kevin, who would never figure it out. About all the future kids who would walk into this classroom and get warned about Mrs. Webster.\n\n\"I think I'll keep it to myself,\" I said. \"It's funnier that way.\"\n\nMrs. Webster's twinkle returned, brighter than ever.\n\n\"Welcome to the club, Mr. Chen.\"\n","narration":null},{"id":6,"number":6,"title":"The Secret Keeper","file":"chapter-6.md","markdown":"# The Secret Keeper\n\nBeing a secret keeper is harder than it sounds.\n\nI couldn't tell Destiny the whole truth—just that Mrs. Webster and I had \"come to an understanding.\" Destiny accepted this with a nod and went back to her robot-speech, which honestly was getting kind of impressive. Last week she asked to \"relocate to the hydration station for the purpose of consuming water,\" and Mrs. Webster had no choice but to say yes.\n\nKevin, of course, never figured it out. And never would.\n\n\"This class is driving me up the wall!\" he announced one Tuesday, after getting another question wrong.\n\nMrs. Webster looked at the wall thoughtfully. \"That seems dangerous, Kevin. Walls are quite vertical. Should I notify the maintenance department?\"\n\n\"I didn't mean—\"\n\n\"Perhaps they could install handles? For your climbing convenience?\"\n\nKevin groaned. I caught Mrs. Webster's eye across the room. She winked. I bit my lip to keep from laughing.\n\nThe weird thing was, knowing the secret didn't make me immune. Mrs. Webster still got me, almost every day. But now it felt different. Like we were playing a game together, instead of her playing a game on me.\n\n\"I could use a hand with these papers,\" I said one afternoon, purely to see what she'd do.\n\nWithout missing a beat, she walked to the science corner, reached into the skeleton model, and detached its plastic hand.\n\n\"Will this do?\"\n\n\"Perfect,\" I said, taking the skeleton hand and using it to wave at Destiny, who stared at me like I'd lost my mind.\n\nThree weeks later, a new kid showed up.\n\nHer name was Emma. She had red hair and freckles and looked absolutely terrified, the way all new kids look on their first day. I remembered that feeling. The lockers, the hallways, the lunch tables where you don't know anyone.\n\nAt recess, I watched the other kids swarm her with warnings.\n\n\"Whatever you do, don't use idioms—\"\n\n\"She takes EVERYTHING literally—\"\n\n\"One time she called a farm about a horse—\"\n\nEmma nodded along, eyes wide, probably thinking the same thing I'd thought: *These kids are pranking me*.\n\nDestiny appeared at my shoulder.\n\n\"Are you going to tell her the truth?\"\n\nI watched Emma receive warning after warning. I thought about my first day. About the horse, the cake, the Webster Twinkle. About sitting in Mrs. Webster's classroom and finally understanding.\n\n\"Where's the fun in that?\" I said.\n\nDestiny smiled. \"You're starting to sound like her.\"\n\nI walked over to Emma.\n\n\"Hey. New kid?\"\n\n\"Yeah.\" She looked at me nervously. \"Emma.\"\n\n\"I'm Marcus. I was new a few months ago.\" I paused. \"About Mrs. Webster...\"\n\n\"The literal teacher? Everyone keeps warning me.\"\n\n\"Yeah, well.\" I shrugged. \"You should definitely listen to them.\"\n\n\"Is she really that weird?\"\n\nI thought about it. About the fifteen years of notes. About the twinkle. About a teacher who found a way to make fourth grade the best part of her day.\n\n\"She's exactly that weird,\" I said. \"Every word of it.\"\n\nEmma didn't look reassured. But she would figure it out. Or she wouldn't. Either way, Mrs. Webster would have fun.\n\nIn class that afternoon, Mrs. Webster welcomed Emma with a warm smile.\n\n\"Wonderful to have you, Emma. I'm so glad you could join us.\"\n\n\"Thanks,\" Emma said nervously. \"I'm, um, happy to be here?\"\n\nMrs. Webster tilted her head. Adjusted her glasses.\n\n*Here we go*, I thought.\n\n\"Happy to be *here*?\" Mrs. Webster said. \"What an interesting phrase. Where exactly is 'here'? This classroom? This school? This planet? 'Here' is quite relative, Emma. Perhaps you should clarify.\"\n\nEmma's mouth opened. Closed. Opened again.\n\nFrom across the room, Mrs. Webster caught my eye and winked.\n\nI winked back.\n\nThen she returned to the lesson, and I returned to my notes, and Emma began her education in the most important subject at Brookdale Elementary:\n\nChoosing your words very, very carefully.\n\n---\n\n*THE END*\n\n*(But not THE END as in \"the conclusion of all things\"—just THE END of this particular story. Mrs. Webster would want me to clarify.)*\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":6,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
